text: People seem to forgot one little fact. The Romans never hung their victims on crossbeams. They hung their victims on upright poles. It was cheaper (one wooden pole for one victim) and greatly more torturous. The Romans reveled in causing great pain. Once nailed to the pole and hung upright a victim couldn't "lift" their body to breathe without great pain. This caused the victim to slowly suffocate to death. In order to speed up the process Roman soldiers would routinely break the legs for anyone who didn't die from suffocation fast enough.  In the original Greek the Gospel writers used the word Stauros (σταυρός) which denotes an upright pale, pole, or stake. Even the Latin word crux means a mere stake.  The crossbeam, appearing as the letter "T", is an ancient pagan symbol for the initial letter of the Pagan God Tammuz; who was the deified Nimrod. This cross symbol has appeared in many pagan religions and rituals through history such as the Egyptian Ankh.

text: To clear the confusion:  Where is the movie on Dionysis? Where is the movie on Ceres, Vulkan, Zeus, Mars, Appolo, Venus, and co? Where is the movie on Amaterasu, Izanami and Izanagi? Where is the movie on Thor and Odin? Where is the movie on El or Baal. Where is the movie on Old Man?  The only reason this bland story is getting relentlessly recycled past reconciliation is because people take it seriously. When in doubt, look at the evidence. In the same way that myths have formed 'evidence' for Perseus, Prometheus, Icarus, the fore mentioned, and literally legions more of characters, one can say that the gospels are 'evidence' for Jesus. But that doesn't work. What then does history say? Actually, save a brief mention which itself is in question, Jesus seems only feasibly to be fictitious. Let me set the stage. Our story begins with a baby and a King Herod slaughtering all infants under the age of two. No such event has ever been listed by historians and this point is only mentioned in a single gospel. When Jesus grows up, he leads thousands as he spreads his word. And yet he's not popular enough to make it into the works of historians. Ancient Rome is actually the best well documented time in history of the ancient world and several 'messiahs' in Jesus's time were mentioned by historians, just not Jesus. When he dies, the day turns dark and many rise up from the dead. Not a mention.  The truth is the gospels were written decades after the alleged event and it shows. Pilate, for instance, is portrayed horribly inaccurately. So why do we have this story? Why do we have any? The gospels began to be written roughly around the year 70. The temple was being destroyed and Vespassian started the first Roman-Jewish war, with his son Titus succeeding him and starting the second. History has shown that in traumatic times, apocalyptic writings flourish, especially ones pertaining to a saviour.  One last argument. Mark, Matthew and Luke have surprised scholars on their similarities. Literally entire chapters have been taken from one word-by-word from the other. The only way this could have happened is if they had the previously 'published' gospel by them as they wrote theirs. So why deliberately change the story? Why 'plagiarize' a text and decide to add your own spin on it? Because that's how fiction works.  Yes, I'm an atheist, but I'm not evil. It was in fact my moral obligation to become an atheist, rather than believe in a paradoxical deity who commands blood sacrifices, condones slavery, condones rape, kills people for collecting sticks on sabbaths, and floods all of humanity.

text: I am a Christian. In reading through the Gospels, I came across some interesting information. After Jesus died and was buried in a tomb that belonged to Joseph of Arimethea, the leaders of  the Sanhedrin went to see Pilate with a demand.They asked him to place a round the clock guard by the grave of Jesus that would last the three days following the death of Jesus. Pilate asked why he should do this. They told him they were afraid the disciples of Jesus would try to move His Body and make the people believe Jesus had risen from the dead as He had said He would three days after His death. Pilate agreed he would do this and placed four guards around the tomb where Jesus was buried. They were replaced around the clock and seals were placed on the rock that sealed the grave. After dawn on Sunday the guards found the stone was rolled back and there was no body in the tomb.A man standijg in the tomb told the guard that Jesus was no longer there, and had risen from the dead. The guards reported what had happened and what they were told. The leaders of the Sanhedrin wanted the guards to say they had left their posts or fallen but Pilate supported the guards. By the time Pilate and the guards came back to the tomb te women the Bible mention (Mary Magdeline and Mary mother of Jesus) had arrived and told them an angel had told them Jesus had risen. The guards came to Pilate later that day and told him they had been approached by the Sanhedrine, wanting to bribe thd guards to state that Jesus was moved from the tomb. They and Pilate refused!  Why has none of this ever been included in any of the movies about Jesus??? Why would they leave this out!!! If you want to verify this information, read the Book of Mark.....all the way trough!

text: There are always arguments in the comments for movies like these.  Can everyone just calm down?  As a Christian, I am not going to shove my religion down the throats of non-believers because people HATE that, and rightfully so.  And for any who don't believe, I am sorry.  I am sorry for the nasty looks the people of the Church give you.  I am sorry for the noses turned in the air.  I am sorry for the hypocrisy.    However, I am not sorry for what I believe in.  I am not sorry that I believe with all my heart in the one true God.  My religion is one I cannot quite wrap my head around, but that's what I take my comfort in, actually.  What kind of God would He be if my tiny, finite, human brain understood it all?  Not much of one.  I find peace in the mystery.  Yet, I know that this world, the people and the experiences and the oceans and the trees did not happen merely by chance.  God did it.  He did it all.  As crazy as it is, as little as I understand, it's the only thing that makes sense.  Just read Romans...Romans 3-11.  It's all there.  Romans 10:13 states that "whoever calls upon the name of the Lord shall be saved."  And it's that simple, y'all...just believe.  Your life will change.  Mine sure did. text: Resurrection? Okay, for discussion’s sake I’m willing to posit that JC died and returned to life. No tricks, no coma or catatonia: he was straight-up _dead_, then lived again. Hey, why not–according to the Bible, there was a lot of that going on then (Mat 27:52-53)! All of which proves…what?      That JC was very special or very lucky? Yes, for sure!      That there is a “god” that created the universe--a universe with _more stars than there are grains of sand on all the beaches of Earth_? That JC was a son of that being? Oh, and somehow also that “deity” himself? No, there is no logical step by which those conclusions automatically follow.      And in any case: If you want to convince people that there's a supernatural being operating in the universe nowadays--occasionally breaking the laws of physics (to work miracles), and requiring worship and obedience--you're going to have to give some _current_ evidence for it. JC's (alleged) resurrection, two thousand years ago, doesn't qualify.

text: An amazing film I recommend to you all. I left religion 12 years ago, so I was skeptic when I bought tickets for this one, and did it mainly for my mother. But I was surprised in such a positive, nice way for 3 reasons: 1) Forget about a blonde, blue-eyed viking as Jesus. We see truer historical accuracy here, with a Jesus that looks Jewish and very similar to the scientific reconstructions of men of his time.  2) This is NOT religious movie made to sell the figure of the Christ, but a detectivesque thriller with  a few action sequences, told from a very fresh perspective: that of a pagan, skeptical Roman soldier. You even get to see in a very clear way never told before the political maneuvers regarding the Jewish Sanderin, the Romans and the Zealot rebels. 3) The focus of the movie is not the death and torture of Jesus, either, which is something that pulled me away from religion personally. This is the first movie in which the perspective is the actual message of Jesus and his resurrection and ascension, and yet, it never becomes lame and religious. The climatic scene, for example, is the transfiguration of Jesus. I've never seen such a frontal, direct scene depicting this event, and yet, it was beautifully done.  Excellent, underrated film, very well acted and directed.
